At the request of {{ill|Mount Tiantai|ja|天台山|12=draft}} in China to {{ill|Enryaku-ji|ja|延暦寺|12=draft}}, seeking copies of Tendai texts that had been scattered in China, Nichien was dispatched to {{ill|Wuyue|ja|呉越国|12=draft}} in {{ill|953|ja|953rd year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Tenryaku 7|ja|天暦7th year|12=draft}}) as an envoy. There, he was granted a purple robe by King {{ill|Qian Chu|ja|銭俶|12=draft}} of Wuyue and received special permission to study at the {{ill|Si Tiantai|ja|司天台|12=draft}} (astronomical observatory). In {{ill|957|ja|957th year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Tentoku 1|ja|天徳元年|12=draft}}), he returned to Japan bringing with him the {{ill|Futen Calendar|ja|符天暦|12=draft}}, a new calendar system not yet known in Japan, along with approximately 1,000 volumes of Buddhist and non-Buddhist texts.
