Emperor [[:en:Emperor Murakami|Murakami]] intended to award Nichien a {{ill|sōgō senji|ja|僧綱宣旨|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/sōgō senji|qq=}} (imperial appointment for monks) in recognition of his achievements, but Nichien declined the honor and instead went to [[:en:Dazaifu (government)|Dazaifu]] in Kyushu. During the [[:en:Kōhō|Kōhō era]] ([[:en:964|964]]–[[:en:968|968]]), he established {{ill|Ōura-ji|ja|大浦寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōura-ji|qq=}} for [[:en:Fujiwara no Morosuke|Fujiwara no Morosuke]].

Nichien's introduction of the Futen Calendar laid the foundation for the development of {{ill|Sukuyōdō|ja|宿曜道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukuyōdō|qq=}} (astrology) in Japan. However, according to the {{ill|Nijūreki|ja|二中歴|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nijūreki|qq=}}, Nichien was not regarded as a Sukuyō master but rather as a {{ill|Rokumeishi|ja|禄命師|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokumeishi|qq=}}, an expert in {{ill|Rokumei|ja|禄命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokumei|qq=}}—a form of divination that determines a person's fate based on bone structure and birth date. It appears his activities were more prominently associated with Rokumei than with Sukuyōdō.

