{{distinguish|Nichiren}}
'''Nichien''' (日延, dates of birth and death unknown) was a [[:en:Tiantai|Tendai]] monk from the mid-[[:en:Heian period|Heian period]]. He was a native of [[:en:Hizen Province|Hizen Province]] and a disciple of {{ill|Ninkan|ja|仁観|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninkan|qq=}}, who held the position of {{ill|Gon-risshi|ja|権律師|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gon-risshi|qq=}}.
At the request of [[:en:Tiantai Mountain|Mount Tiantai]] in China to [[:en:Enryaku-ji|Enryaku-ji]], seeking copies of Tendai texts that had been scattered in China, Nichien was dispatched to {{ill|Wuyue|ja|呉越国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wuyue|qq=}} in [[:en:953|953]] ({{ill|Tenryaku 7|ja|天暦7年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenryaku 7|qq=}}) as an envoy. There, he was granted a purple robe by King {{ill|Qian Chu|ja|銭俶|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Qian Chu|qq=}} of Wuyue and received special permission to study at the {{ill|Si Tiantai|ja|司天台|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Si Tiantai|qq=}} (astronomical observatory). In [[:en:957|957]] ({{ill|Tentoku 1|ja|天徳元年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tentoku 1|qq=}}), he returned to Japan bringing with him the {{ill|Futen Calendar|ja|符天暦|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futen Calendar|qq=}}, a new calendar system not yet known in Japan, along with approximately 1,000 volumes of Buddhist and non-Buddhist texts.
Emperor [[:en:Emperor Murakami|Murakami]] intended to award Nichien a {{ill|sōgō senji|ja|僧綱宣旨|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/sōgō senji|qq=}} (imperial appointment for monks) in recognition of his achievements, but Nichien declined the honor and instead went to [[:en:Dazaifu (government)|Dazaifu]] in Kyushu. During the [[:en:Kōhō|Kōhō era]] ([[:en:964|964]]–[[:en:968|968]]), he established {{ill|Ōura-ji|ja|大浦寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōura-ji|qq=}} for [[:en:Fujiwara no Morosuke|Fujiwara no Morosuke]].
Nichien's introduction of the Futen Calendar laid the foundation for the development of {{ill|Sukuyōdō|ja|宿曜道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukuyōdō|qq=}} (astrology) in Japan. However, according to the {{ill|Nijūreki|ja|二中歴|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nijūreki|qq=}}, Nichien was not regarded as a Sukuyō master but rather as a {{ill|Rokumeishi|ja|禄命師|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokumeishi|qq=}}, an expert in {{ill|Rokumei|ja|禄命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokumei|qq=}}—a form of divination that determines a person's fate based on bone structure and birth date. It appears his activities were more prominently associated with Rokumei than with Sukuyōdō.
